    # [Scene: Floodplain Market | Dawn]

    scene bg ch13_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Camera shutters, the low hum of a generator, murmurs that rise and fall like surf]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tense, rapid strings under a steady drumbeat]
    "You wake inside a phone-screened moment: your face on three feeds, your name on a hundred tongues. The exposé—dozens of documents, emails, and whistleblower testimony—landed overnight. It spread like spilled water through the town: slick, unstoppable, urgent."
    "You stand behind a milk-crate podium because someone thought it would look better for the cameras. Your palms remember the pen you once nearly signed with; the ink of compromise is still under your nails as"
    "memory. Kai is at your elbow, his smile thin, hands restless. Dr. Leila holds a tablet with scanned pages, her jaw set. Nita is planted before you like a bright, stubborn buoy—determination written in the way"
    "she rests her hands on the crate. Reverend Sol watches from the back, his silence a steady weight that steadies the room."
    "You inhale brine and coffee and too many people's hope. It tastes like copper."
    show anita_nita_ramirez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    anita_nita_ramirez "You did it, Mara. You made them answer. That's—' (She swallows, voice rough with something like pride and fear) '—that's huge."
    show mara_linh_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_linh_alvarez "It isn't done.' (Your voice is quieter than you expect; it needs to be sharp) 'It needed to be heard. It needed to be true."
    show dr_leila_osei at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_leila_osei "The science corroborates the conflicts. Those retrofit tests were— (She taps the tablet) —poorly conducted, data cherry-picked. The contracts? They tie municipal accounts to Blackbrand's financing arms. It's all there."
    hide anita_nita_ramirez
    show kai_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_navarro "And the press—regional already picked it up. They're calling it a potential pattern, not just Marisport."

    "Reporter" "Mara Linh Alvarez, did you expect legal retaliation from Blackbrand when you released those documents?"
    "You feel every pair of eyes like a current under your feet. You could give the answer that rallies people—defiant, loud—or the careful answer that keeps lawyers from choking on their coffee."

    menu:
        "Speak plainly—'Yes, and we expected worse.'":
            "You let the words cut the air: 'Yes. We expected worse. We put the truth first.' The crowd shifts; a cheer starts like a rising tide."
        "Stay measured—'We acted to protect our neighbors.'":
            "You say, 'We acted to protect our neighbors.' It sounds steadier. Phones nod; a local anchor gives a quick approving gasp. Kai's shoulders relax a fraction."

    # --- merge ---
    "The cameras eat your answer and vomit it back to the region within minutes. For a fleeting hour the town hums with a new electricity—neighbors trade facts under tarps, someone pins copies of the redacted memos"
    "to a corkboard, children chase a wilting balloon between crates of greens. You feel a fierce, raw joy—like the wind pressing at the backs of your plans."
    "The cameras eat your answer and vomit it back to the region within minutes. For a fleeting hour the town hums with a new electricity—neighbors trade facts under tarps, someone pins copies of the redacted memos"
    "to a corkboard, children chase a wilting balloon between crates of greens. You feel a fierce, raw joy—like the wind pressing at the backs of your plans."
    "Then the other wind rises."
    # [Scene: Community Hall | Midday]
    hide mara_linh_alvarez
    hide dr_leila_osei
    hide kai_navarro

    scene bg ch13_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The printer's staccato, a lawyer's hurried whisper; outside, the distant thump of an idling security van]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussive strings escalating; occasional brass stabs]
    "The first lawyer's envelope is stiff with threat: defamation, damaging a corporation's 'reputational capital,' and—worse—a demand for retraction and costly reparation. The language is surgical, designed to bleed time and money. A second envelope is thicker:"
    "a cease-and-desist with an injunction threat. The third is a notice of arbitration. They arrive like low tide pulling away hope."
    "Dr. Leila lays them on the table as if laying out bones."
    show dr_leila_osei at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_leila_osei "They're moving fast. They have in-house counsel lined up, and—' (She inhales, voice thin) '—they've already served a preliminary injunction to freeze the municipal contingency funds tied to the site."

    "Reverend Sol" "Paper can be a weapon as much as it can be a shield. They will file until someone folds."
    show evelyn_black at right:
        zoom 0.7

    evelyn_black "There are responsible ways to adapt, and there are reckless campaigns that endanger livelihoods and delay protection. We will seek accountability where there is malice. Marisport deserves safety with oversight."
    "You want to call her all the names that stack behind the emails—theres' the accounting of contractors who 'disappeared' failures from public records, the structuring of shell companies to hide conflicts. Instead, you feel the room contract into the size of your chest."
    show kai_navarro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_navarro "They're trying to make this about you when it's about their books."
    "You think of the vendor lists whose receipts tied them to Blackbrand's supply chain, of the small leases that could be canceled the next day. You think of Nita, and the idea of her market stall being picked off piece by piece makes your stomach hollow."

    menu:
        "Push for a public rebuttal—call Evelyn a liar on the livestream":
            "You almost speak into the microphone, ready to name names. Kai's hand tightens on your sleeve—'Not like that,' his look says. You swallow the riposte back down."
        "Mobilize legal aid quietly—hold off on public escalation":
            "You nod to Dr. Leila. 'We buy time,' you tell the room. It's not dramatic, but it's a plan. Someone murmurs approval, someone else curses softly; the mood shifts to the sobering work of defense."

    # --- merge ---
    "The town is awake now; outraged op-eds and sympathetic anchors fan the embers, but the company's counterpunch lands faster than the cheers."
    "The town is awake now; outraged op-eds and sympathetic anchors fan the embers, but the company's counterpunch lands faster than the cheers. Overnight, trucks arrive at the Blackbrand site, heavy units with private security logos—black vans,"
    "grim men with earpieces. They plant flags and build physical distance where there once were conversations."
    "At the market, suppliers call in trembling voices: corporate procurement has cut ties pending 'review.' A loan covenant is invoked; a vendor's micro-lender freezes a line of credit because municipal funds are tied up in litigation."
    "A delivery of kerosene, essential for the winter market heaters, is listed as diverted. Small things that connect to people's daily safety are severed."
    "You watch Nita argue with a courier who says the bank refuses to release payment; her hands, the hands that gut fish and count bills, fly as if they could catch the falling day."
    hide dr_leila_osei
    show anita_nita_ramirez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    anita_nita_ramirez "They're choking us until we stop shouting. That's what this is."
    "You want to do more than want; you want to tear the legal pages into confetti and scatter them on the docks. Instead you file a counter-notice, you email civil-rights hotlines, you coordinate pro-bono counsel. The work is small and necessary and bitterly slow."
    # [Scene: Floodplain Market Entrance | Afternoon]
    hide evelyn_black
    hide kai_navarro
    hide anita_nita_ramirez

    scene bg ch13_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Heated voices, the rattle of a wheelchair, the cry of a child cutting through panic]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings reach a raw, discordant peak; distant sirens]
    "What appears next feels like a line being crossed from legal warfare to intimidation. A security detail blocks the chief route where market vendors receive deliveries. They claim authorization—a temporary property hold based on a pending"
    "arbitration order. Their badge numbers are small and carefully unreadable. Their boots scuff wood and salt."
    "Nita steps into the path of the truck, her frame small but unbowed."
    show anita_nita_ramirez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    anita_nita_ramirez "You won't stop us from feeding this town."

    "Security" "Move aside or we will detain you for obstruction."
    "A shove—sharp, mechanical—sends Nita stumbling back. The crowd surges. Someone screams. A crate of beets spills, dark and glistening across the wet planks."
    show kai_navarro at right:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_navarro "Get off him!"
    show mara_linh_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_linh_alvarez "Leave him!"
    "The security detail radios for back-up. A second van rolls up, lights dull and professional. Someone—perhaps a journalist, perhaps an opportunist—screams for the police. The market, once a place of commerce and low, honest laughter, becomes an auditorium for fear."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A loud barked command; then two more men in uniforms move to form a line]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussion crashes; then a high sustained violin note slices through everything]
    "The crowd presses like a panicked tide. Phones point; a camera captures Sol's fall at the precise angle required for outrage."
    "You taste blood at the back of your throat—adrenaline, salt, the metallic tang of fear—and the world narrows to the sound of your own breathing and the thudding of your heart against an armor of helplessness."
    # [Scene: Community Hall | Evening — Aftermath]
    hide anita_nita_ramirez
    hide kai_navarro
    hide mara_linh_alvarez

    scene bg ch13_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A low, weary murmur; keys tapping; the distant lullaby of waves]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low cello underpinning a minor-key piano]
    "The civil suits land like winter storms—heavy, inevitable. Blackbrand sues you for defamation. The company also sues the municipal council for breaching pre-negotiated arbitration clauses. A string of vendor contracts are called in default after 'non-performance'"
    "clauses are invoked. Two local suppliers fold under pressure. The municipal contingency fund remains frozen pending arbitration."
    "You spend the night taking names, calling volunteers, drafting petitions. You sleep in snippets—half an hour here, a swallowed nightmare there. Each time you wake you check the stock ticker the town uses in the back-of-house"
    "group chat; the numbers are small and meanless to an individual life, but the pattern is a tightening vise."
    "Kai Navarro doesn't sleep either. He sits up on the rooftop orchard with his legs dangling over the edge, sketchbook closed in his lap. When you find him later, dawn thin and salt-white, his face has the tired firmness of someone who has been holding back a flood."
    show kai_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_navarro "We opened at least one window. People know now."
    show mara_linh_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_linh_alvarez "They know—and they hurt.' (You cannot keep your voice steady) 'We started a fight that they didn't have to wage on the backs of every vendor here."
    "Kai Navarro: (turns to you) 'Do you regret it?'"
    "Mara Linh Alvarez: (hear the confession before you speak it) 'Sometimes. Mostly, I can't tell which parts I regret. Telling the truth felt right. Seeing Nita on the ground felt wrong. The two are braided.'"
    "Kai Navarro reaches and takes both of your hands, fingers cold, holding them as if to keep you from collapsing into the tide. In that small rectangle of shared warmth there is an entire argument left"
    "unspoken—about risk and strategy, about when to escalate and when to shield the vulnerable. For a moment you search his face for an exit strategy, for a map, for something to steady you."

    kai_navarro "We stay. I stay.' (He says it, and his voice is softer than it has been, but iron-true) 'Not for the headline. For the people who are still standing. For Nita, for Sol. For you."
    "Mara Linh Alvarez: (leaning into him, letting your forehead rest against his) 'I don't want to be the reason someone loses their roof.'"

    kai_navarro "Then don't shoulder it alone. Let me be there. Let us—' (He stops, the sentence failing under the weight of recent bruises) '—let us be a small, stubborn lighthouse."
    "You close your eyes. The image is ridiculous and perfect: a crooked beacon in a town that will keep getting bashed by storms but refuses to go dark entirely."
    "Reverend Sol arrives on the rooftop without the ceremony of speech. He sits between you, cane across his knees."

    "Reverend Sol" "History rarely makes room for clean endings. It makes room for witness. It makes room for those who keep a light when the rest go out. You turned a light on. The darkness answers. That does not make the light wrong."
    "You listen, and the warmth in your chest is complicated: relief, exhaustion, and a sharp, constant ache that is the price of being correct and being harmed at the same time."
    # [Scene: Media Venues / Regional Coverage Montage | Night]
    hide kai_navarro
    hide mara_linh_alvarez

    scene bg ch13_3be532_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Overlapping clips, the static of social feeds, the distant clack of a teleprompter]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A slow, elegiac swell that refuses to resolve]
    "The regional press amplifies your story and magnifies the company's counter-narrative. The legal filings become part of the public record; pundits argue about tactics as if the people whose lives are squeezed by the injunctions are"
    "mere case studies. Donations trickle in to support legal fees, but they do not replace the supply chains choked by corporate pressure. Volunteers stand watch in shifts to ensure market stalls remain open. You count who"
    "shows up each morning—tired, resolute faces—and it is both smaller and braver than the crowd that cheered at the beginning."
    "You write op-eds that read like a ledger of small cruelties. You sign affidavits. You sleep on a futon at the community hall between consults. You are more tired than you knew possible."
    "There are nights when you consider leaving, and there are mornings when the smell of salt and soil and broken beets pulls you back."
    "Kai Navarro finds you on the promenade some evening, the sky bruised with storm-clouds. He has your compass in his hand—your father's scuffed brass piece, the one you always carry—and he puts it gently into your palm. The metal is cool and oddly comforting."
    show kai_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_navarro "You set it down at the hearing. You said you needed someone else to steer sometimes.' (He smiles, sad) 'I found it. Thought you'd like it back."
    "You close your fingers around the compass and feel its dented edge, a familiar weight to anchor you."
    show mara_linh_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_linh_alvarez "I didn't expect it to cost this much."

    kai_navarro "Nobody does.' (He swallows) 'But some of us think it's worth the cost. I don't know if they're right. I know I won't walk away."
    "You hold the compass till the metal warms, until your hands remember a steadier rhythm. It is not a victory token; it is a reminder that someone trusted you enough to ask you to lead."
    hide kai_navarro
    hide mara_linh_alvarez

    scene bg ch13_3be532_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A gull cries once, long; a whispered prayer; the rasp of wind through netting]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Solo piano in a minor key, small and persistent]
    "When you step up the promenade to where the old lighthouse silhouette faces the sea, you map losses in your head: two suppliers, a frozen fund, bruised bodies, a market that will take months to rebuild"
    "confidence. You also map gains: the truth is public, the documents are out of the vault, regional NGOs now have the evidence they can use. There is no clean victory—only labor, and a long legal fight"
    "ahead."
    "Kai Navarro slides his arm through yours. He does not pull you close in a triumphant gesture; instead he offers steady company."
    show kai_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_navarro "We will keep going. Maybe they'll win in court. Maybe we'll be bankrupted by legal fees. Maybe the town will hold. Maybe it won't. None of that changes what we chose."
    show mara_linh_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_linh_alvarez "Is that enough?"
    "Kai Navarro: (after a long moment) 'It's all I can offer.' (His voice breaks, but he doesn't let it shatter) 'Stay. Fight. Grieve when it's necessary. Let me be in the trenches with you.'"
    "You look out at the water—an endless, impartial horizon. The sea will keep coming, indifferent to court rulings and op-eds, to human strategies of defense. The truth in the papers might slow one project and embolden another, but it will not stop the rising tide."
    "You fold the compass into your palm and make a small, decisive motion: you will not sign away the town's voice for convenience. You will not let fear of retaliation be the thing that silences witness."
    "But you also allow yourself the grief of what has been lost—the market stalls, the shaken bodies, the sudden, ugly reality that exposing truth invites a different kind of harm."
    "You and Kai stand together on the promenade in the thin light, the town behind you bruised but not broken into silence. The road ahead is a ledger of legal battles, suppliers to coax back, nights without sleep, and the slow, patient work of rebuilding trust."
    "You do what you have always done: you keep a lamp lit and circulate it among the people you love. It is not a bright beacon—more like a match in a dark room—but it is enough for now."
    hide kai_navarro
    hide mara_linh_alvarez

    scene bg ch13_3be532_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fades to a single, low sustained cello note]
    "You exhale, the sound small and final. There is no tidy ending—only the steady decision to stay and endure. The papers will keep coming. The lawsuits will pile. The market will be quieter for a time. You will be more tired. You will be more vigilant."
    "You turn to Kai and Reverend Sol and Nita; they are there, scarred and stubborn. You nod once, to all of them and to yourself. The light you lit will be kept alive by a battered, determined set of hands."

    scene bg ch13_3be532_8 at full_bg
    "THE END"
